            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Kkotnori (flower viewing) and sangchungaek (flower picking) are words used every day as people travel around the country to admire colorful flowers. Some famous flower festivals in spring include Yeouido Spring Flower Festival, Jinhae Gunhangje Festival, Gurye Sansuyu Flower Festival, Korean Goyang International Floriculture and Jeju Canola Flower Festival.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Summer starts in June and ends in August, which is the time for beach lovers. Korea has the advantage of many beaches with beach festivals taking place everywhere. If the Boryeong Mud Festival at Daecheon Beach is the most famous internationally, festivals at five major beaches such as Haeundae and Gwangalli also attract crowds of visitors with fireworks displays and concerts. vibrant. Yangyang in Gangwon-do is ideal for surfers. Daegu, famous for being the hottest city in Korea, is where the Chimac festival takes place. Here you will have unforgettable experiences with fried chicken and cold beer.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Clear blue skies cover Korea during autumn. Tourists should go to the forest during autumn in Korea because the bright red, yellow, and orange autumn leaves are an extremely lively and captivating scene. Seoraksan, Naejangsan and Jirisan mountains are famous destinations for autumn leaf lovers.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Winter starts in December and ends in February. The weather is cold, making it an ideal time for winter sports lovers, especially skiing and snowboarding. Visitors can also experience ice fishing at the Hwacheon Sancheoneo ice festival and the Pyeongchang salmon festival. Winter is also an ideal time to go hiking at Seonjaryeong Pass and Taebaeksan Mountain in Gangwon-do. Both of these routes have stunning scenery that lasts until early March.</p>

            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Entry conditions</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">The Korean government said it will reissue C-3 short-term visas to tourists from level 1 countries, including Vietnam, from June 1. The Korean government has removed many disease prevention restrictions, however, international visitors still need negative Covid-19 test results (PCR or rapid test) before entering the country. Within 72 hours of entering Korea, visitors will have to take a PCR test. The country also lifted the requirement to wear masks outdoors.</p>

            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Move</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Vietnam has direct flights to Korea through airlines such as Vietjet Air, Vietnam Airlines of Vietnam and Korean Airlines, Asiana Airlines of South Korea.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">There are currently direct flights to Korea from Vietnamese airlines such as Vietjet Air (ticket price from 540,000 VND for the Hanoi - Busan route, and for the Ho Chi Minh City - Seoul route, ticket price from 1,450,000 VND, all excluding taxes, fees, and transportation). consignment agent); Vietnam Airlines (Ho Chi Minh City - Seoul route from 4.6 million VND, Hanoi - Busan route from 8 million VND, ticket includes taxes, fees and checked baggage). Additionally, guests can buy tickets from Korean Airlines. Asiana Airlines' ticket price is from 8 million VND per route, Korean Air's is from 13 million VND per route from Ho Chi Minh City or Hanoi to Seoul, including taxes, fees and checked baggage.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Passengers entering the country can use the AREX express train, which connects Incheon Airport Terminals 1 and 2 to Seoul Station and vice versa. Travel time is about 43 minutes. Ticket price is 9,500 won (nearly 180,000 VND) per person.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Domestic transportation: subway, bus, taxi...</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Subway: in big cities like Seoul, Busan, Incheon, visitors can use Google Maps or the subway finder app to know the nearest station. The train's operating hours are from 5:30 to 24:00. Advantages: No traffic jams, safe, fast and an opportunity to experience a new way of traveling. Disadvantages: During three hours or special occasions, you often have to stand, only focusing in big cities.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Bus: Present in most provinces and cities. Visitors just need to look up google maps to find the nearest bus station. There is a trip every 10-15 minutes or follow the electronic board at the station. Advantages: Convenient to go to many places, low cost - Disadvantages: Waiting time can affect travel plans.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Taxi: Call the switchboard, hail a taxi on the street or use a taxi booking app. From 24h to 4h increase 20% fee. Advantages: Clean, airy, affordable, flexible schedule. Disadvantages: Highest cost among all types. Be sure to check whether the meter is turned on or not.</p>

            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Visiting sites</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>DMZ</b>: this place not only holds haunting memories of the Korean War seven decades ago, but is also a pristine ecosystem. This is one of many destinations tourists should explore during their stay in Korea.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Famous tourist destinations in Seoul</b>: include palaces such as Gyeongbokgung, Changdeokgung, Changgyeonggung, Deoksugung; National Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art; Gwanghwamun Square; Bukchon Hanok Village; Namsan Park and Namsan Tower; The Blue House (residence of the Korean president), is open to visitors with 4 tours per day. Travelers must register online at least three weeks before their trip. In addition, Seoul is also famous for many streets such as Dongdaemun fashion street, Itaewon neighborhood, Insangdong, Hongdae...</p>
