            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Experience nightlife</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Korea is a sleepless country, the lights are on all night, so the evening here is still as lively and bustling as the day. Many shopping areas and night markets are open until late, so visitors can enjoy shopping and entertainment.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Night shopping</b>: Dongdaemun Fashion Market is located in the capital Seoul. This is a great place for you to shop for trendy clothes at affordable prices. The most famous shopping area here is Doota Mall.</pclass="handbook-content-1>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Night market food tour</b>: depending on where you go, visitors can enjoy a variety of dishes.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">You can eat fried chicken, stir-fried beef, steamed and fried pork intestines... right in the middle of the night at Jeonju nambu market in Jeollabuk. At Busan Bupyeong Kkangtong night market, local specialties are sold in abundance such as fried beans stuffed with vegetables, seafood and vermicelli; fish cake... If you visit Daegu Seomun night market with more than 80 food stalls serving dishes such as pig stomach, grilled skewers, sushi and grilled meat... Other night markets that visitors can visit are Daein Art in Gwangju, Bamdokkaebi in Seoul... At Noryangjin seafood wholesale market, the largest fish market in Seoul, visitors can enjoy seafood until midnight.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Night attractions</b>: cultural heritage sites in central Seoul are quiet and contemplative when night falls. Naksan Mountain Road of Hanyangdoseong Seoul City Wall stretches from Hyehwamun Gate to Heunginjimun Gate, and is a very interesting night walking route. The approximately 1-hour walk along the fortress in a warm space under dim lights is an unforgettable experience.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Deoksugung and Changgyeonggung Palaces are open until 9:00 p.m. (tickets sold until 8:00 p.m.) and are gorgeously lit at night. Changdeokgung Palace, a UNESCO world heritage site, offers a "Moonlight" tour from spring to fall. Buying this tour, visitors will be accompanied by a tour guide and watch traditional performances. Gyeongbokgung Palace is also open in the evening from spring to fall. You can fly in a hot air balloon and enjoy stunning views of the fortress from a height of 150 meters.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Gaming</b>: Korean gamers and gaming teams are famous around the world. And playing online games is a favorite entertainment among young people in this country. You can visit internet cafes equipped with computers to play games. These shops are often equipped with the most modern and fastest computers; best keyboard and headset. Customers coming to the restaurant are also given ramyeon noodles (instant noodles) and spicy rice cakes. Korea has a youth protection law, so underage children cannot play games between 10pm and 9am the next day. Therefore, visitors need to bring their passport to go to the restaurant after 10:00 p.m.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Jjimjilbang</b> is a Korean-style sauna. Here, you can eat, relax and even sleep over. People often like to eat boiled eggs with sweet rice wine while chatting with friends at jjimjilbang.</p>

            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Beautiful photography locations</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Ganmun Beach</b> in Gangneung area, Gwangwon Province is not too large but has many lovely photo spots, helping you take perfect pictures.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">The coastal city of <b>Woljeongri</b> on Jeju Island is the perfect place to see the emerald blue ocean. Tewoo Beach on Jeju Island is famous for its unique horse-shaped lighthouse and breathtaking sunsets.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Gamcheon Cultural Village</b> in Busan is the perfect backdrop for beautiful photos thanks to its colorful houses located on the mountainside.</p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/Home/Handbook/Korea/korea-6.jpg" width="100%" />
            <p class="note-img">Andong City</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Dongpirang Mural Village</b> in Tongyeong, Gyeongsangnam Province is a small port town. Coming to this place, you feel like you are lost in a different world with colorful walls.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>The train village in Gunsan</b>, Jeollabuk Province is an attractive photo spot thanks to the houses located opposite each other across the decommissioned train tracks.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Penguin Village in Gwangju</b> has houses and alleys decorated with beautiful little trinkets.</p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/Home/Handbook/Korea/korea-7.jpg" width="100%" />
            <p class="note-img">Bulguksa Temple in Gyeongsangbuk Province</p>

            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">New destinations</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Ikseondong, Seoul</b>: located in the center of the capital, Ikseandong has many small alleys with rows of hanok houses (traditional houses) built in the 1920s. Today, these houses are renovated to serve as restaurants and bars. Korean-style cafes and bars.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Euljiro, Seoul</b>: this area used to be a maze of alleys. Today, this place is bustling with shops with ancient architecture, but the interior has been renovated with a modern style. Nogari Alley in this area has many restaurants specializing in serving delicious beer and nogari to visitors.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Geahangro, Incheon</b>: old buildings are brought back to life and converted into businesses like an art gallery, a 100-year-old house converted into a fried chicken shop. Incheon is the closest city to Seoul, so it is very convenient for tourists to visit.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Hwangnidangil, Gyeongju</b>: Once the capital of the Silla Kingdom for nearly 1,000 years, today Hwangnidangil city is famous for its many rooftop cafes, where visitors can view hanok houses from above. After sightseeing, you can also freely shop at many souvenir shops on the street.</p>

            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Unique places to stay</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">To gain a deeper understanding of Korean culture and nature, you should experience a full day and night at traditional accommodation establishments, KTO Vietnam advises.</p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/Home/Handbook/Korea/korea-8.jpg" width="100%" />
            <p class="note-img">Chungcheongnam province</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Gyeong Won lae Ambassador: Traditional houses stand out amid the modern scene in Songdo, Incheon This hotel has a hanok-like structure and gives visitors the feeling of living in a traditional house. However, because many visitors are not used to sitting on the floor, there are beds and tables in a modern style.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Gurume Resort in Andong, Gyeongsangbuk-do: this is a real hanok house, converted into a motel. During your stay, you can visit the book cafe for rest and entertainment,</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Ragung Hotel in Gyeongju, Gyeongsangbuk-do has an open-air but still private bathing space, helping you relax after a long day of sightseeing.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Hanok Village gives you the opportunity to admire beautiful sea views through traditional fences. In addition to the above hotels, there are also many hanok guesthouses in Seoul and Jeju.</p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/Home/Handbook/Korea/korea-9.jpg" width="100%" />
            <p class="note-img">A small corner in Bukchon Hanok village</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Shilla Jeju gives you a luxurious camping experience, with tents as big as living rooms, including beds, sofas, and tables. Despite being outdoors, these tents are still fully equipped and bring a pleasant feeling. You can also stay at a similar place, the Kensington Flora hotel in Pyeongchang, Gangwon or the Mangsang Auto Campine in front of Mangsan beach.</p>

            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Eat and drink</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Soju: The most famous Korean beverage. Soju is sold at convenience stores diluted, and is a popular drink because of its affordable price.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Makgeolli: this traditional low alcohol wine has a sweet and aromatic taste. Makgeolli wine is often used by people with pajeon (green onion pancake) made from flour, meat and vegetables.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Craft beer can be found almost everywhere in Korea such as Gangneung, Jeju, Andong and Sunchang, you can easily buy it at convenience stores, supermarkets...</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Bibimbap</b> is a particularly popular mixed rice dish with eye-catching colors and a variety of ingredients including fresh vegetables, beef, gochujang chili sauce, rice and sesame oil. Bibimbap served in a hot stone bowl is an extremely popular dish.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Fried chicken</b> is a dish that often appears in movies. The chicken has a crispy exterior and soft meat on the inside. The dish attracts diners because it combines many traditional spices, often served with cold beer.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Bulgogi</b> consists of thinly sliced ​​beef marinated with sweet soy sauce, sugar, and garlic, then pan-fried or grilled over charcoal. Seoul-style Bulgogi is prepared in a unique way, using a special grill pan. The concave part of the pan is used to cook meat, while the upper part of the pan is used to cook sauce, usually containing mushrooms, vegetables and vermicelli. In other regions, there are also ways to cook bulgogi.</p>
            <img src="~/Content/Images/Home/Handbook/Korea/korea-10.jpg" width="100%" />
            <p class="note-img">In people's meals, kimchi is an indispensable dish</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Some other equally famous dishes are spicy rice cakes, ginseng stewed chicken, hongeo samhap (sliced ​​fermented stingray, pork and kimchi), chopped raw octopus marinated in sesame oil, grilled pork belly, cold noodles...</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Korean royal cuisine</b> is the recipes for preparing dishes exclusively for the royal family during the Joseon Dynasty (1392-1910). The best, freshest ingredients selected from all regions across Korea are sent to prepare each meal with 12 dishes including vegetables, meat and seafood. Sinseollo is a broth dish with beef broth, meatballs, fried dough, vegetables, and gujeolpan, which is a thinly coated flour crepe rolled with beef and vegetables. These are two famous dishes in royal cuisine.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Patbingsu</b>: made from shaved ice, milk, sweet bean powder, fruit, rice cakes, syrup and many other "toppings".</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2"><b>Tteok or rice cake</b>, is made of steamed rice flour and then molded into many different shapes. This is one of the most popular traditional snacks in the country. During traditional holidays and special occasions, rice cakes are an indispensable dish in ceremonies.</p>

            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">What to buy in Korea?</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Cosmetics: Korean skin care products are very popular because of their effectiveness. Face masks are one of the most widely used products. City center areas such as Myeong dong and Hongdae have many cosmetic stores.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Ginseng: Korean ginseng is famous all over the world for its perfect quality, especially steamed and dried red ginseng, processed into many different products such as candy, jelly, plaster... Type of functional food This healthy product can be purchased at tax stores, Namdaemun market and famous tourist areas.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Traditional souvenirs: mirrors with traditional lacquered handles, shell key chains, silk lucky bags, travel mugs painted with antique patterns...</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Shops in palaces and museums are ideal places to buy traditional souvenirs. Cheongwadae Sarangchae Center and the national souvenir center in Insa-dong are two examples. For tourists looking for more unique and memorable items, Namdaemun market is a perfect choice.</p>


            <p class="handbook-title-1 mt-3">Necessary information</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Wi-Fi paradise: Subway stations, cafes, shopping malls and most tourist attractions have free, high-speed wifi.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">No cash needed: All you need is a credit card. Except for a few small businesses that transact in cash, the rest everywhere accept credit cards, even for small transactions.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Convenient public transportation: A large subway system, railways stretching across the country and fast inter-city buses help visitors travel around Korea easily.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Easy, fast food delivery: From famous restaurant chains, eateries to coffee shops, cakes..., you can order them to deliver anywhere, even if you visit the parks along the Han River and request to be shipped to.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">Safe streets, low crime rate: You almost never see or hear about robberies, thefts or attacks. At major tourist destinations, there is always tourist police support.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2">The country never sleeps: many convenience stores, restaurants, shopping streets and even ATMs are open 24/7. You can buy food, withdraw money, and top up your public transportation card even at midnight.</p>
            <p class="handbook-content-1 mt-2 mb-4">Friendly signs for international visitors: Most public areas such as subways and bus stations have signs in English. Tourist locations and facilities also have signs in many languages ​​such as English, Japanese, Chinese...</p>
